WASHINGTON , July 17 -LRB- Xinhua -RRB- -- <ENAMEX TYPE="OKAY">About 376 sheep imported from Europe will be killed and incinerated as a forewarning against the possible spread of a disease connected to mad cow disease , U.S. officials said Monday</ENAMEX> .
The sheep were in three flocks in Vermont , and tests showed four of them were carrying a transmissible spongiform encephalopathy -LRB- TSE -RRB- , a type of ailment that causes scrapie in sheep and mad cow disease in cattle , said officials with the Agriculture Department .
The department decided to acquire and then kill the sheep , the owners of which will be compensated and kill them .
The carcasses will be incinerated .
Scientists are to conduct tests to see what kind of TSE infected the sheep .
<ENAMEX TYPE="OKAY">The Vermont sheep flocks to be destroyed were built with sheep imported from Belgium and the Netherlands in 1996 .
The Agriculture Department learned in 1998 the sheep could have been exposed to feed contaminated with mad cow disease</ENAMEX> .
